				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Consider the open interval <m>I=(1,2)</m>.
Prove each of the following.
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      The points <m>1</m> and <m>2</m> are accumulation points of <m>I</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>p \in I</m>, then <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of <m>I</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>p \lt 1</m> or <m>p \gt 2</m>, then <m>p</m> is not an accumulation point of <m>I</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Show that a point <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of the intervals <m>(a,b)</m>, <m>(a,b]</m>, <m>[a,b)</m>, and <m>[a,b]</m> if and only if <m>p \in [a,b]</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that the point <m>p=0</m> is an accumulation point of <m>A =\{\frac{1}{n}| n \in \mathbb{N}\}</m>.
Are there any other accumulation points of <m>A</m>?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            For each set <m>A</m>, find the set of accumulation points <m>A'</m>.
In each case, sketch a proof to justify your assertions.
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>A=\{-17,1,\pi,42\}</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>A=[1,3) \cup (3,5)</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>A = [1,3) \cup \{17\}</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>A = \mathbb{R}</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>A= \mathbb{Q}</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>A = \mathbb{Z}</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\displaystyle M=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty} (-1-\frac{1}{n}, 1+\frac{1}{n})</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\displaystyle M=\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty} (-\frac{1}{n}, \frac{1}{n})</m>
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that if <m>A</m> is finite, then <m>A</m> has no accumulation points.
That is, if <m>A</m> is finite, then <m>A'=\emptyset</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            State the contrapositive of the previous problem.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Determine whether the converse of Problem 4.16 is true or false. Justify your assertion.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Provide an example of a set <m>A</m> with exactly two accumulation points.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="4in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Given sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, determine whether each of the following is true or false.
If the statement is true, prove it.
Otherwise, provide a counterexample.
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of <m>A \cap B</m>, then <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of <m>A \cup B</m>, then <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of <m>A</m> or <m>p</m> is an accumulation point of <m>B</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>

                

